    <section xml:id="DoublePeriodForm">
        <title>The Double Period</title>
        <introduction>
            <title>The Double Period</title>
            <p>A <term>double period</term><idx><h>double period</h><h>definition of</h></idx> consists of at least 4 phrases and is comprised of an <term>antecedent group</term><idx><h>antecedent group</h></idx> and a <term>consequent group</term><idx><h>consequent group</h></idx>. The first two phrases in a double period are the antecedent group and the final two phrases are the consequent group, which ends with a cadence that <q>answers</q> the less conclusive cadence (or <q>question</q>) that ended the antecedent group.</p>
            <p>The melodic scheme of <em>abab’</em> (four phrases) is commonly encountered in a double period. A double period with this melodic scheme would be described as a <q><em>parallel</em> double period</q> because both the antecedent group and consequent group begin with the same melody.</p>
